● Exactly. This is the key architectural question. Let me categorize:

  Any instance (shared storage — Envoy mesh OK):
  - workflow → ScyllaDB
  - persistence → ScyllaDB/MongoDB
  - authentication → ScyllaDB
  - rbac → ScyllaDB
  - resource → ScyllaDB
  - repository → MinIO
  - ai_memory → ScyllaDB
  - title → ScyllaDB
  - search → shared index
  - backup_manager → MinIO
  - media → MinIO

  Must reach specific node (direct connection):
  - node_agent → controller must talk to a specific node's agent
  - event → pub/sub listeners are in-memory on the node they subscribed. Publish on node B won't reach node A's subscribers
  - file → local filesystem ops must hit the node where files live (MinIO-backed is fine through mesh)
  - log → local log files
  - dns → BadgerDB is local per-node

  Single leader (mesh OK but only one exists):
  - cluster_controller → one leader elected via etcd
  - discovery → single instance

  So the fix isn't "everything through mesh" — it's two tiers:

  1. Mesh tier: stateless or shared-storage services → route through Envoy :443, any instance handles any request
  2. Direct tier: stateful/local services → ResolveServiceAddr returns specific host:port

  Does this match your understanding? If so, I can add a flag to service configs (e.g. "MeshRoutable": true) so ResolveServiceAddr knows when to return the mesh address vs the direct port.

